@node description "Description"

    Statty creates and maintains an echomail flow database by analyzing your
    Fido tosser logfile. 

    Currently it supports the following tossers: Spot, Foozle, MailManager
    and CrashMail.

    It creates a nice statistics file that shows just how much mail you've 
    received in each of the areas you import. This file is fully localized 
    (As is the rest of Statty).

    @{" English statistics file " link examples/statty.out/main} 
    @{" Danish statistics file  " link examples/statty.out.dk/main} 
    @{" French statistics file  " link examples/statty.out.fr/main} 

    @{" Database file           " link examples/statty.db/main}
    @{" Database format         " link dbformat}

@endnode
@node requirements "Requirements"

    WB 2.1+ (locale.library).
    rmh.library 3.1 (Included).

@endnode
@node installation "Installation"

    Copy rmh.library to libs: if you don't have it already.

    Copy statty.rexx to rexx:

    If Statty has been translated to your language copy the catalog file to 
    locale:catalogs/

    If you use Spot then have a look at the @{" logspotxport " link logspotxport} script. If you 
    install this script Statty will be able to add echomail written by you 
    to it's database. 

    And finally: Please read the @{" notes " link tossers} about the tosser you're using.

@endnode
@node usage "Usage"

    rx rexx:statty.rexx TOSSER/A,LOG/K/A,AREA/K/A,SDIR/K,K=KEEP/S,
    KEEPNAME/K,A=NOALL/S,T=NOTOYOU/S,O=KEEPOLD/S

    When there are no arguments on the commandline, Statty looks for a file
    named 'statty.prefs' in mail:, s: or env: and tries to read the
    arguments from that. 

    You can also specify which configfile to use with the special CFGFILE
    keyword. Eg: rx statty.rexx CFGFILE=mail:statty.spot.prefs 

    The format of Statty's config file is simple: either all arguments on
    one line (Separated by spaces) or one argument per line.

    TOSSER/A      Required. Must be either 'Spot', 'Foozle', 'MailManager'
                  or 'CrashMail'

    LOG/K/A       Required. Full path to your tosser's logfile.

    AREA/K/A      Required. Full path to your tosser's areas file.

    SDIR/K        Where do you want to place Statty's output files. Defaults 
                  to the same directory as your tosser's logfile. This is 
                  also the directory where you must place the @{" excludefile " link excludefile}

    K=KEEP/S      Keep a backup of tosser logfile. Defaults is no backup.

    KEEPNAME/K    If the KEEP switch is set you can change the filename (Not
                  the path) of the backed up log with this option. Default 
                  is to append '.statty' to original log filename.

    NA=NOALL/S    Don't include areas with no flow (Zero messages) in the 
                  output file. Default is to include them.

    NT=NOTOYOU/S  Don't show messages to or from you in the outputfile. 
                  Default is to show them. This switch only works with the 
                  @{" tossers " link tossers} that supports logging of echomail from or to you.

    O=KEEPOLD/S   Don't delete areas that you no longer import from the database.
                  Default is to delete them.

    Entering 'rx statty.rexx ?' gives you the template. 

    Examples:
    rx rexx:statty.rexx Spot log=logs:Spot.log.max area=mail:max/spot.areas 
    sdir=logs:spot KEEPOLD

    rx rexx:statty.rexx Crashmail log=logs:crashmail.log 
    area=mail:crashmail.prefs sdir=logs:cm

@endnode
@node excludefile "The excludefile"

    The excludefile is a list of areanames, one per line. All of these areas
    won't be added to the database. See @{" notes on tossers " link tossers} for more
    information.

    The excludefile must be named 'statty.exclude' and must be placed in the 
    @{" SDIR " link usage} directory

    @{" Example excludefile " link examples/statty.exclude/main}

@endnode
@node tossers "Notes on tossers"

    Please read the section about your tosser. 

    @{" Spot            " link spot}
    @{" Foozle          " link foozle}
    @{" MailManager     " link mailmanager}
    @{" CrashMail       " link crashmail}

@endnode
@node spot "Spot"

    Spot writes the user areaname to the log. Which means that you can have
    two different tagnames using the same areaname in the log.
    Statty will check for this and abort if it finds the same user areaname 
    twice in your Spot.areas file. You have to make sure that you use unique 
    usernames for each area.

    If you want to use an excludefile you have to write the user areaname in 
    the file, not the tagname.

    If you want to enable logging of echomail written by you, have a look at
    the @{" logspotxport " link logspotxport} script. When you've installed the script Statty will
    automatically add the extra info to your database.

@endnode
@node foozle "Foozle"

    Foozle writes the user areaname to the log. Which means that you can
    have two different tagnames using the same areaname in the log.
    Statty will check for this and abort if it finds the same user areaname
    twice in your Foozle.areas file. You have to make sure that you use
    unique usernames for each area.

    If you want to use an excludefile then you have to write the user
    areaname in the file, not the tagname.

@endnode
@node mailmanager "MailManager"

    You must set the loglevel to at least 3. 

    MailManager writes the tagname to the log. But only the first 30 
    characters. So you can have two different tagnames appear like same area
    in the log. 
    Statty will automatically add the 'duplicate areas' to your excludefile.
    If you don't already use an excludefile, Statty will automatically 
    create one for you.

    If you want to manually add areas to the excludefile then you have to 
    write the tagname in the file, not the user areaname.

@endnode
@node crashmail "CrashMail"

    You must set the loglevel to at least 3. 

    The @{" NOTOYOU " link usage} switch is automatically switched off
    because CrashMail doesn't log that you received or sent echomail.

    There's no 'user areanames' in CrashMail - it only uses the tagname. And
    you must use the tagname as well if you want to use an excludefile.

@endnode
@node translation "Translation"

    If you want to translate Statty to your language then have a look at the
    @{" statty.cd " link catalogs/statty.cd/main} file. All you need to do is translate all the strings and 
    send the new statty.cd to @{" me " link author}.
    
@endnode
